---
import LocalizedCalculatorPage from '../components/LocalizedCalculatorPage.astro';
import SlippageCalculator from '../components/SlippageCalculator.tsx';
---

<LocalizedCalculatorPage
  lang="en"
  slug="slippage-calculator"
  title="DEX Slippage Calculator"
  description="Estimate swap slippage, minimum received amount, and total execution cost for DEX trades."
  faq={[
    {
      q: "What causes slippage on decentralized exchanges (DEX)?",
      a: "Slippage on a DEX occurs because automated market makers (AMMs) use liquidity pools with a constant product formula. Larger trades consume more liquidity and move the price further from the quoted rate. Low liquidity pools, high volatility, and large order sizes all increase slippage."
    },
    {
      q: "How do I reduce slippage on Uniswap and other DEXes?",
      a: "Split large orders into smaller trades, use limit orders on DEX aggregators like 1inch or CoW Swap, trade during high-liquidity periods, and choose pools with deeper liquidity. For large swaps, DEX aggregators route across multiple pools to minimize total slippage."
    },
    {
      q: "What slippage tolerance should I set for DEX swaps?",
      a: "For major token pairs like ETH/USDC, 0.5% is usually sufficient. For mid-cap tokens, 1-3% is common. For micro-cap or newly launched tokens, 5-12% may be needed. Setting slippage too low causes failed transactions; setting it too high exposes you to sandwich attacks."
    },
    {
      q: "What is a sandwich attack and how does slippage relate to it?",
      a: "A sandwich attack is when a bot detects your pending swap, places a buy order before yours (front-running) to push the price up, then sells after your trade executes. Higher slippage tolerance gives bots more room to extract value. Using private mempools or MEV protection tools helps prevent this."
    },
    {
      q: "How much slippage is normal for a large DEX trade?",
      a: "For trades under $10,000 on major pairs, slippage is typically 0.1-0.3%. For trades between $10,000-$100,000, expect 0.3-1%. Trades above $100,000 can experience 1-5% or more depending on pool depth. Always check the price impact shown by the DEX interface before confirming."
    },
    {
      q: "Is slippage different on Ethereum vs Layer 2 DEXes?",
      a: "Slippage depends on pool liquidity, not the blockchain layer. Ethereum mainnet DEXes like Uniswap often have the deepest liquidity and lowest slippage for major pairs. Layer 2 DEXes on Arbitrum or Optimism may have higher slippage for the same pair due to thinner liquidity pools, but lower gas fees can offset the cost."
    }
  ]}
>
  <SlippageCalculator slot="calculator" lang={'en'} client:load />
</LocalizedCalculatorPage>

<style>
  .calc-wrapper { width: 100%; }
</style>
